00:16:02,613 --> 00:16:04,365
Believes in human frailty...

257
00:16:04,453 --> 00:16:06,683
No. Something's missing from her.

258
00:16:06,773 --> 00:16:07,967
She's wrong.

259
00:16:08,693 --> 00:16:10,206
She wants on this jury.

260
00:16:10,293 --> 00:16:12,682
Somebody hurt her and she wants revenge.

261
00:16:14,933 --> 00:16:17,003
How the hell do you know that?

262
00:16:17,973 --> 00:16:19,167
I don't know.

263
00:16:21,093 --> 00:16:24,165
Either you put a stop
to this happy horseshit or I walk.

264
00:16:25,413 --> 00:16:26,323
Walk.

265
00:16:28,453 --> 00:16:32,082
Here's the deal: If I lose with your jury,
you do the explaining.

266
00:16:33,013 --> 00:16:34,765
Your Honor, may I continue?

267
00:16:34,853 --> 00:16:37,970
We'd like to excuse
Jurors three, four and six.

268
00:17:28,253 --> 00:17:30,972
Hi. You're home early for a change.

269
00:17:34,973 --> 00:17:36,486
Your mother called.

270
00:17:37,053 --> 00:17:39,283
She has her "bad feeling."

271
00:17:43,693 --> 00:17:45,968
Every now and then, she gets one right.

272
00:17:48,453 --> 00:17:49,488
You okay?

273
00:17:52,173 --> 00:17:53,526
Something's up.

274
00:17:54,213 --> 00:17:56,966
They deliberated for 38 minutes.

275
00:18:01,693 --> 00:18:03,763
Oh, honey, I'm sorry.

276
00:18:06,053 --> 00:18:10,251
What the hell did they expect?
The man is as guilty as can be.

277
00:18:10,653 --> 00:18:13,372
Wasn't a jury anywhere gonna let him off.

278
00:18:14,253 --> 00:18:15,288
Yeah.

279
00:18:17,293 --> 00:18:18,408
Except one.

280
00:18:18,813 --> 00:18:19,689
What?

281
00:18:25,093 --> 00:18:26,731
Not fucking guilty!

282
00:18:27,253 --> 00:18:29,448
Oh, my God! You lying...

283
00:18:29,613 --> 00:18:30,887
...sack of shit!

284
00:18:30,973 --> 00:18:32,964
Thirty-eight minutes, my jury!

285
00:18:35,453 --> 00:18:37,205
Thirty-eight minutes!

286
00:18:37,573 --> 00:18:39,928
- You did it!
- My jury! I'm too good!

287
00:18:43,933 --> 00:18:46,493
- <i>Glad you could stick around.</i>
- <i>It's your dime.</i>

288
00:18:46,573 --> 00:18:47,642
Sorry to keep you waiting.

289
00:18:47,733 --> 00:18:51,089
Mr. Milton got pinned down in Indonesia
longer than expected.

290
00:18:51,453 --> 00:18:52,966
Good morning, Caprice.

291
00:18:53,533 --> 00:18:55,046
Good morning, Mr. Heath.

292
00:18:55,133 --> 00:18:56,361
Your messages.

293
00:19:00,253 --> 00:19:01,447
Not bad, huh?

294
00:19:02,413 --> 00:19:04,005
You can play it cool if you want...

295
00:19:04,093 --> 00:19:07,130
...but when I first walked in,
my jaw was on the floor.

296
00:19:10,493 --> 00:19:11,528
This is our home office.

297
00:19:11,613 --> 00:19:13,126
We have many
international arrangements...

298
00:19:13,213 --> 00:19:15,727
...so Mr. Milton spends a great deal
of his time in the air.

299
00:19:15,813 --> 00:19:17,246
Three o'clock, we got the Greeks.

300
00:19:17,333 --> 00:19:19,164
Am I a good cop or a bad cop?

301
00:19:19,253 --> 00:19:20,925
We may not need a good cop.

302
00:19:21,013 --> 00:19:22,082
I love it.

303
00:19:22,693 --> 00:19:26,652
In addition to our corporate clients
we're representing 25 foreign countries:

304
00:19:26,733 --> 00:19:29,691
The Mideast, the Balkans,
Central America, West Africa...

305
00:19:29,773 --> 00:19:32,241
Interesting work, but travel-intensive.

306
00:20:25,453 --> 00:20:26,568
Behind you.

307
00:20:28,173 --> 00:20:29,162
I'm sorry.

308
00:20:29,253 --> 00:20:30,971
Please. Kevin Lomax.

309
00:20:31,453 --> 00:20:32,568
John Milton.

310
00:20:32,653 --> 00:20:33,972
Nice to meet you.

311
00:20:39,413 --> 00:20:40,209
So?

312
00:20:41,133 --> 00:20:43,010
Have we been treating you well?

313
00:20:43,093 --> 00:20:44,162
Very well, thank you.

314
00:20:44,253 --> 00:20:46,164
And your wife, she's had a good time?

315
00:20:46,253 --> 00:20:49,609
She sure has. It's been great.
The whole thing's been great.

316
00:20:52,173 --> 00:20:53,572
That's our secret:

317
00:20:53,853 --> 00:20:55,491
Kill you with kindness.

318
00:20:57,933 --> 00:20:59,332
What's your secret?

319
00:20:59,973 --> 00:21:01,406
I couldn't say.

320
00:21:01,853 --> 00:21:03,127
You were a prosecutor.

321
00:21:03,213 --> 00:21:06,762
Out of law school.
Five years in the Jacksonville D.A.'s office.

322
00:21:08,773 --> 00:21:11,048
Sixty-four straight convictions.

323
00:21:12,653 --> 00:21:13,802
What a number!

324
00:21:14,413 --> 00:21:16,005
I like to be in court.

325
00:21:16,333 --> 00:21:17,971
I didn't plea out a lot.

326
00:21:18,973 --> 00:21:20,042
What's that like?

327
00:21:20,133 --> 00:21:23,170
One day you put them away,
the next you set them free.

328
00:21:24,173 --> 00:21:25,731
Takes a little getting used to.

329
00:21:25,813 --> 00:21:27,371
Pays better, though, doesn't it?

330
00:21:27,453 --> 00:21:29,011
Yes, it does.

331
00:21:30,373 --> 00:21:34,810
That math teacher, the Gettys case...
now I hear you were brilliant.

332
00:21:35,533 --> 00:21:37,285
Prosecutor dropped the ball.

333
00:21:37,373 --> 00:21:38,408
Really?

334
00:21:39,133 --> 00:21:40,805
You think your guy was guilty?

335
00:21:40,893 --> 00:21:42,121
I didn't say that.

336
00:21:42,213 --> 00:21:43,441
What'd you say?

337
00:21:44,573 --> 00:21:45,847
How's this:

338
00:21:46,173 --> 00:21:49,165
I began the case with a clear conscience.

339
00:21:56,173 --> 00:21:58,004
I was sure you had a secret.

340
00:22:01,373 --> 00:22:02,601
The men's room.

341
00:22:02,893 --> 00:22:05,361
Upstairs men's room
in the Duval County courthouse.

342
00:22:05,453 --> 00:22:08,013
There's a hole in the wall to the next room.

343
00:22:08,093 --> 00:22:10,846
I spent five years listening
to juries deliberate.

344
00:22:10,973 --> 00:22:12,691
- I love it.
- Love it all you want.

345
00:22:12,773 --> 00:22:14,001
Just don't repeat it.

346
00:22:14,093 --> 00:22:17,403
I'm not sure the Florida Bar Association
would appreciate it.

347
00:22:17,493 --> 00:22:19,370
My lips are sealed.

348
00:22:19,933 --> 00:22:22,845
You don't really want to go back
to Florida, do you?

349
00:22:26,933 --> 00:22:28,127
Walk with me.

350
00:22:47,813 --> 00:22:49,166
What do you think?

351
00:22:50,373 --> 00:22:52,170
Some people can't handle it.

352
00:22:53,653 --> 00:22:54,847
It's peaceful.

353
00:22:56,173 --> 00:22:58,050
My sentiments exactly.

354
00:22:59,853 --> 00:23:04,244
Fill in the résumé for me.
Tell me, your father, what does he do?

355
00:23:04,533 --> 00:23:07,969
I never got to know my father.
He passed away before I was born.

356
00:23:08,133 --> 00:23:10,522
My mother raised me. Just the two of us.

357
00:23:10,613 --> 00:23:11,887
She never remarried?

358
00:23:11,973 --> 00:23:14,043
She wasn't married the first time.

359
00:23:14,413 --> 00:23:17,371
That can't be easy in a town
like Gainesville, can it?

360
00:23:18,213 --> 00:23:20,249
I don't think it's easy anywhere.

361
00:23:22,533 --> 00:23:23,602
Holy shit!

362
00:23:24,933 --> 00:23:26,844
Different when you're looking down,
isn't it?

363
00:23:26,933 --> 00:23:28,571
Yes, it is.

364
00:23:29,413 --> 00:23:30,732
Oh, my God.

365
00:23:31,173 --> 00:23:32,322
Your mother...

366
00:23:32,573 --> 00:23:34,006
...what's she like?

367
00:23:34,773 --> 00:23:37,241
She's a preacher's daughter. She's tough.

368
00:23:37,413 --> 00:23:40,769
She's worked in a poultry plant
for as long as I can remember.

369
00:23:40,893 --> 00:23:44,772
She's got a church she really likes,
so she's usually there or they go out...

370
00:23:44,853 --> 00:23:46,764
They do a lot of volunteer work.

371
00:23:46,853 --> 00:23:50,368
"Behold, I send you out
as sheep amidst the wolves."

372
00:23:52,013 --> 00:23:53,241
So they say.

373
00:23:53,893 --> 00:23:55,167
It didn't rub off?

374
00:23:55,253 --> 00:23:56,925
The Book? The Church?

375
00:23:57,293 --> 00:23:58,851
No, I'm on parole.

376
00:23:59,053 --> 00:24:01,408
Early release for time served.

377
00:24:05,013 --> 00:24:07,288
A lot of potential clients down there.

378
00:24:07,733 --> 00:24:09,166
Are we negotiating?

379
00:24:10,093 --> 00:24:11,128
Always.

380
00:24:12,733 --> 00:24:14,689
Can I ask you a question, then?

381
00:24:15,453 --> 00:24:17,887
Why do you need a criminal department?

382
00:24:18,133 --> 00:24:21,648
Our clients break the law like anyone else.

383
00:24:24,853 --> 00:24:28,084
I'm just tired of sending their business
across the street.

384
00:24:28,773 --> 00:24:31,651
- Are you offering me a job?
- I'm thinking about it.

385
00:24:33,373 --> 00:24:36,570
I know you've got talent.
I knew that before you got here.

386
00:24:37,093 --> 00:24:40,290
It's just the other thing I wonder about.

387
00:24:41,733 --> 00:24:42,848
What thing?

388
00:24:44,933 --> 00:24:45,968
Pressure.

389
00:24:47,053 --> 00:24:49,089
It changes everything. Pressure.

390
00:24:49,373 --> 00:24:52,285
Some people, you squeeze them,
they focus.

391
00:24:52,733 --> 00:24:54,052
Others fold.

392
00:24:56,133 --> 00:24:58,363
Can you summon your talent at will?

393
00:24:59,053 --> 00:25:00,930
Can you deliver on a deadline?

394
00:25:02,293 --> 00:25:03,885
Can you sleep at night?

395
00:25:05,373 --> 00:25:07,091
When do we talk about money?

396
00:25:07,173 --> 00:25:08,242
Money?

397
00:25:12,333 --> 00:25:13,846
That's the easy part.

398
00:25:14,813 --> 00:25:16,804
<i>They call this part of Fifth Avenue,</i>
<i>Carnegie Hill.</i>

399
00:25:16,893 --> 00:25:19,612
<i>You've got the park right across the street,</i>
<i>and the reservoir.</i>

400
00:25:19,693 --> 00:25:21,285
<i>Best jogging in New York.</i>

401
00:25:21,373 --> 00:25:23,045
<i>Mount Sinai Hospital is up the street.</i>

402
00:25:23,133 --> 00:25:24,725
<i>Some excellent schools.</i>

403
00:25:25,493 --> 00:25:28,212
Not on the top of Mr. Milton's list
when he bought this building...

404
00:25:28,293 --> 00:25:30,602
...but great neighborhood for children.

405
00:25:30,693 --> 00:25:31,967
Great building.

406
00:25:33,053 --> 00:25:35,442
Follow the money all the way to the top.

407
00:25:35,613 --> 00:25:38,810
You've got the managing director,
Eddie Barzoon, on 16.

408
00:25:38,973 --> 00:25:41,567
And, of course, Mr. Milton has the tower.

409
00:25:44,733 --> 00:25:46,451
- You must be Mary Ann?
- Yes, I am.

410
00:25:46,533 --> 00:25:48,763
Welcome. I'm Jackie Heath.

411
00:25:50,053 --> 00:25:51,566
It's nice of you to come by.

412
00:25:51,653 --> 00:25:53,848
Oh, please. We live across the hall.

413
00:25:54,013 --> 00:25:55,890
- You're kidding.
- Right there.

414
00:25:56,293 --> 00:25:58,249
It's just two apartments per floor?

415
00:25:58,333 --> 00:26:02,087
- You didn't tell them about it?
- It can speak for itself.

416
00:26:03,293 --> 00:26:04,442
<i>Voilà!</i>

417
00:26:10,333 --> 00:26:11,607
Oh, my God!

418
00:26:12,853 --> 00:26:15,128
It's what they call a "Classic Eight."

419
00:26:15,333 --> 00:26:17,801
Be careful. I don't have a map.
I don't want you to get lost.

420
00:26:17,893 --> 00:26:22,125
We had them paint it white. Let you see it
naked before you pick your palette.

421
00:26:22,213 --> 00:26:23,407
What am I picking?

422
00:26:23,493 --> 00:26:24,812
Palette. Your colors.

423
00:26:24,893 --> 00:26:25,848
Oh, yes.

424
00:26:28,413 --> 00:26:30,404
I need to warn you about one thing.

425
00:26:30,493 --> 00:26:34,327
There are going to be some
very envious people down at the firm.

426
00:26:34,493 --> 00:26:37,963
There aren't many of these apartments.
They're a partner's perk.

427
00:26:38,053 --> 00:26:40,248
You must've made quite an impression.

428
00:26:40,453 --> 00:26:44,048
Oh, my God, three bedrooms.
You know what that means?

429
00:26:44,693 --> 00:26:45,648
Babies.

430
00:26:45,853 --> 00:26:47,969
It took us six years to get in here.

431
00:26:51,973 --> 00:26:53,486
Unbelievable.

432
00:26:55,453 --> 00:26:56,932
Thank you very much.

433
00:27:01,093 --> 00:27:03,004
Are you really this good?

434
00:27:03,893 --> 00:27:05,645
I sure as hell hope so.

435
00:27:06,933 --> 00:27:08,844
They must want you pretty bad.

436
00:27:10,533 --> 00:27:11,727
Look, Mar...

437
00:27:12,933 --> 00:27:15,811
...I'm only getting behind this
if you're on board.

438
00:27:16,053 --> 00:27:17,725
If you want to go home...

439
00:27:18,373 --> 00:27:19,647
...I'm with you.

440
00:27:19,933 --> 00:27:21,002
Sure.

441
00:27:21,653 --> 00:27:24,372
Let's go back to Gainesville,
back to the condo.

442
00:27:24,693 --> 00:27:28,732
You keep scrounging for clients and
I'll keep repossessing cars for Akamian.

443
00:27:28,893 --> 00:27:32,203
And maybe, just maybe,
if we kill ourselves...

444
00:27:33,333 --> 00:27:37,645
...in about five years we can afford a baby
and a weekend shack at Gulf Shores.

445
00:27:38,173 --> 00:27:39,731
Are you shitting me?

446
00:27:45,333 --> 00:27:46,448
I love you.

447
00:27:47,013 --> 00:27:48,526
I love you, too.

448
00:27:52,373 --> 00:27:54,364
Tadashi Osumi, Media.

449
00:27:54,533 --> 00:27:56,364
Walter Krasna, Maritime Law.

450
00:27:57,053 --> 00:27:58,532
Bashir Toabal, Energy Law.

451
00:27:58,613 --> 00:28:00,285
I run the Islamic subgroup.

452
00:28:00,373 --> 00:28:03,092
Joyce Rensaleer, Mergers and Acquisitions.

453
00:28:03,253 --> 00:28:06,165
Eddie Barzoon, Managing Director and...

454
00:28:06,973 --> 00:28:08,201
...Real Estate.

455
00:28:08,333 --> 00:28:10,847
Pradeed Resh, Intellectual Properties.

456
00:28:11,413 --> 00:28:14,291
Christabella Andrioli,
International Trade and Customs...

457
00:28:14,373 --> 00:28:15,886
...EC and G-7.

458
00:28:18,213 --> 00:28:19,612
There it is, Kevin.

459
00:28:19,973 --> 00:28:21,247
The whole team.

460
00:28:21,693 --> 00:28:24,366
Welcome to Milton, Chadwick and Waters.

461
00:28:24,733 --> 00:28:27,247
So what do you think?
You can change the furniture if you like.

462
00:28:27,333 --> 00:28:28,891
I guess it'll do.

463
00:28:29,213 --> 00:28:30,692
Until something better comes along?

464
00:28:30,773 --> 00:28:32,525
Kevin Lomax, Pam Garrety.

465
00:28:33,253 --> 00:28:34,606
Nice to meet you.

466
00:28:34,933 --> 00:28:36,969
Pam was at the Brooklyn D.A.'s office
for 14 years...

467
00:28:37,053 --> 00:28:39,726
...so she knows her way
around the local scene.

468
00:28:39,893 --> 00:28:41,963
You'll expedite his bar application?

469
00:28:42,053 --> 00:28:45,090
It's in the pipeline.
For now, you'll work <i>pro hac vice</i>.

470
00:28:45,173 --> 00:28:47,607
I petitioned Florida
for a letter of good conduct.

471
00:28:47,693 --> 00:28:51,527
And I prepared, at Mr. Milton's request,
an overview of the Moyez case.

472
00:28:51,893 --> 00:28:52,882
The Moyez case?

473
00:28:54,613 --> 00:28:56,046
<i>Move, move, move!</i>

474
00:29:16,613 --> 00:29:17,932
What do you think?

475
00:29:18,013 --> 00:29:20,527
It's a health code case and it's a loser.

476
00:29:22,653 --> 00:29:24,132
So what's the point?

477
00:29:24,813 --> 00:29:27,964
He wants to see if I'll plea-bargain.
It's a test, right?

478
00:29:29,013 --> 00:29:30,332
Isn't everything?

479
00:29:32,493 --> 00:29:34,927
It's an 18th-century Italian silk damask...

480
00:29:35,013 --> 00:29:38,972
...with an embossed floriated pattern
of undulating acanthus leaves.

481
00:29:39,133 --> 00:29:40,486
Lovely, isn't it?

482
00:29:42,253 --> 00:29:44,289
And this is about what?

483
00:29:44,653 --> 00:29:45,688
The price?

484
00:29:46,373 --> 00:29:48,762
It's about $2,000 a panel.

485
00:29:49,973 --> 00:29:51,292
We'll take it...

486
00:29:51,893 --> 00:29:53,087
...at $1,400.

487
00:29:53,293 --> 00:29:54,931
You made it.

488
00:29:56,733 --> 00:29:58,928
I thought you said it was impossible.

489
00:29:59,013 --> 00:30:01,163
I thought you said it was important.

490
00:30:08,973 --> 00:30:10,531
<i>Go get them, man.</i>

491
00:30:10,613 --> 00:30:12,843
<i>Tell him, "Cut that shit down!"</i>

492
00:30:13,133 --> 00:30:16,011
<i>I know what they're doing over there!</i>
<i>That's right!</i>

493
00:30:17,053 --> 00:30:19,726
<i>Tell him, "Take all that noise</i>
<i>back to Africa. "</i>

494
00:30:29,373 --> 00:30:32,012
Good afternoon.
I'm looking for Phillipe Moyez.

495
00:30:44,213 --> 00:30:46,681
Look, I'm not sure I'm making myself clear.

496
00:30:46,773 --> 00:30:49,606
Moyez, you need him? To speak with him?

497
00:30:50,333 --> 00:30:51,812
Show him your boots.

498
00:30:54,213 --> 00:30:56,773
You're saying he's down here
in the basement?

499
00:30:57,373 --> 00:30:58,408
In the dark?

500
00:30:58,493 --> 00:31:00,563
Where do you think I'm taking you?

501
00:31:10,413 --> 00:31:12,449
I thought I would recognize you...

502
00:31:14,413 --> 00:31:15,687
...but I do not.

503
00:31:17,253 --> 00:31:18,288
Mr. Moyez?

504
00:31:20,453 --> 00:31:21,886
We've never met.

505
00:31:22,693 --> 00:31:24,923
I'm Kevin Lomax. I'm a lawyer.

506
00:31:26,053 --> 00:31:27,805
I'm here about the animals.

507
00:31:29,493 --> 00:31:32,132
We have an investment in blood.

508
00:31:34,053 --> 00:31:36,248
Think of it as spiritual currency.

509
00:31:37,973 --> 00:31:39,645
"Spiritual currency."

510
00:31:41,893 --> 00:31:44,930
Look, Mr. Moyez,
I'm going to need your help with this.

511
00:31:49,893 --> 00:31:51,804
What is the name of the man...

512
00:31:51,893 --> 00:31:53,565
...who will prosecute us?

513
00:31:54,573 --> 00:31:55,562
